english:
  title: Evening of the Lantern Festival
  author: Lee In-ro
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Lightning whips crack—thunder's voice rings out,
    and spring's essence pools first in the ten-thousand-year cup.
    Beneath the silver candle's glow the water clock drips slow,
    while jade pipes sing, and warm wind stirs in answer.
    The immortal peach, heavy with dew, bends its laden boughs,
    and the sacred pods, breathing mist, burst open leaf by leaf.
    On the palace road the moon shines bright, all instruments boil with sound—
    the palace maidens vie with one another, singing the song of purple clouds.
  footnotes:
    - The 'ten-thousand-year cup' (萬歲杯) is a ceremonial toast wishing for eternal longevity and imperial blessing, here evoking a festival celebration.
    - The 'immortal peach' and 'sacred pods' are auspicious symbols of longevity and good fortune in Chinese tradition.
    - The 'song of purple clouds' (紫雲回) likely refers to an ancient celebratory or courtly song, suggesting the refined entertainment of the palace.
